### 4. Config Safety (Build Freeze Rule)
#### [MODIFY] [expo-template/src/store/configStore.ts](file:///c:/WebDev/websiteBuilder/KaggleGithubV1/expo-template/src/store/configStore.ts)
- Update [getSafeConfig](file:///c:/WebDev/websiteBuilder/KaggleGithubV1/expo-template/src/store/configStore.ts#43-48) to validate required properties and throw errors during development rendering if corrupt.
- Freeze the configuration objects (`Object.freeze(theme)`) in production/non-demo mode so runtime mutation via [patchConfig](file:///c:/WebDev/websiteBuilder/KaggleGithubV1/expo-template/src/store/configStore.ts#56-60) is blocked, adhering to the build freeze rule.

## Verification
1. **End-to-end flows**: Open the Next.js admin dashboard and use it to add a stall to Supabase. Check Supabase to make sure it's there. Then, open the Expo App. It fetches from Supabase in the background, writes to SQLite, and updates the list seamlessly.
2. **Offline UI**: Turn off your computer's Wi-Fi. Open the Expo app. The Stalls and Announcements screens should still populate instantly using standard Expo SQLite.
3. **Config Safety**: Triggering a [patchConfig({ theme: ... })](file:///c:/WebDev/websiteBuilder/KaggleGithubV1/expo-template/src/store/configStore.ts#56-60) action in the App will silently fail or throw a TypeError, proving runtime modifications are disabled post-build.
